title: A8 E3DV6 63mm Bowden Carriage - ABL12mm - Optional Chain

description.text:
Just a small contribution to a almost perfect E3DV6 Bowden Carriage and Chain from TNS!

I needed a good ABL-Sensor mount, and never was a fan of the Back-Side one and i was looking forward to install a Fancy-Chain.
.
So i decided to put a ABL-Sensor mount onto the Carriage.
I moved the ABL-Sensor mount as far to the right as i was comfortable with, that it doesn't get bumped into the Frame or something else and stay close to the nozzle.
Also the ABL-Sensor mount point is alligned with the Nozzle on the Y-Axis, so you just have to set a X-Offset, which is 28mm on this one.

People was asking if the Chain from TNS will fit, when the ABL-Sensor is sitting on the right side of the Carriage: The answer was, sadly, No :/
The Chain mounting Plate that TNS designed, was screw'd on top of the normal Carriage Backplate and was blocking the spot for the ABL-Sensor. The ABL-Sensor was too long and would not fit... So Chain or ABL - Your choice!

"Dang it i want BOTH!!"
So:
Get rid of that "extra" Chain mount thingy and design a new Cap, which normally just holds the Extruder in place, seriously that was a way too easy printed part anyway :D
It has now included the Chain-Mount as you can see on the pictures.
Sorry for the picture quality, but i forgot to make pictures 'before' i put all together...
And my crappy Handy-Cam did not made it better, sorry... again...
You better watch the parts with Thingiverse-Preview ^^

I included all needed parts in this Package:
The Carriage itself, it is the 63mm E3DV6 one with the 12mm ABL-Sensor mount
The Cap for Chain mount

Also included to complete the package are:
A "normal" Cap
The Chain Motor mount
The Chain pieces

If you decide to print the Chain you will need "27!" chain pieces, 1 more as for the normal chain of TNS.
The mount point moved closer to the Carriage, to stabilize the mounting point as it was too weak in my opinion, thats why you need 1 more piece now.

Thanks again TNS for your Design and to all the other Guys that worked on the Chain before TNS remixed it - I rlly appreciate all that nice share a like of you, and of course your hard work thumbsup

Moo,
Otter

description.text:
I wasn't 100% happy with the 5/16" threaded rod application. I decided to buy an 8mm Lead Screw kit that came with coupler, lead screw, and bearing brackets. I swapped out the pineapple coupler for the 5mm to 8mm flex coupler, and popped the bearing out of the bracket that came with the kit. I also swapped out the nut trap for the one displayed here. I used the round brass nut with 4 x M3 bolts. I believe they were 10-12mm M3 bolts. You could use screws to make sure it's seated properly, but the holes on the nut trap should be tight enough to make your own threads when adding the bolts.

Lastly, I wanted to brace up the 8mm rod, so I took the Z Lower and created something similar for the bottom of the Z Rails. This is for the 1" or J version of the MPCNC 525. Also, I'm using this with the MPCNC Universal Mount. I don't think the original tool mount will cause any issues, but if so, let me know, and I can add a different model with adjustments. I'll throw in the Fusion 360 file when I get back to the office, so you can make your own adjustments if desired.

Pictures will come shortly! Sorry, I forgot to take a pic of the nut trap before inserting it into the assembly. If I ever have to break it down again, I'll be sure to add it at a later date. Also, here is the kit I purchased, so you can see all of the pieces and how they're used: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01H1PXE5Y/

Just a side note, I had to change the steps/min down to something like 800 for the Z-Axis. I haven't had a chance to check or calibrate anything else, should it need it. I'll update this post with any adjustments when/if they happen.

Cheers!

I have a 6040 CNC router that I needed a fastening device to hold the work piece in place. It is mostly sheets of different materials which I machin in, in different thicknesses. These types of fasteners have been used for many years so they should work fine for a CNC router. This step blocks are designed to be used with M6 bolt and M6 nut. Recommend to print them at 100% infill for maximum strength Not recommended to use on other than wood, plastic, wax, etc. Use at your own risk

title: Shellplate Lock/Stop Tool for Hornady Lock-n-Load Progressive Reloading Press
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
You could, of course, buy the lovely red-anodized aluminum tool from Hornady (I have one, it's great. But also overkill and overpriced). Really... they should've included this chunk of plastic with the press. The first time I got my shellplate stuck (and didn't yet have the fancy Hornady wrench) I was VERY irritated.

To use it to loosen/remove the shellplate, click the shellplate FORWARD by a half-click, and press the tool down into the two slots of the shellplate toward the front of the press. Then use your handy hex/allen key to loosen the bolt, while pressing down on your fancy new tool to make sure it remains deeply seated. The shellplate will rotate backwards slightly until the stop/lock tool stops it against the frame of the press and you can crank away with the hex wrench.

To use it to tighten the shellplate... well, it should be self-explanatory. Note that you REALLY don't need your shellplate on too tight. Just tight enough to stay put for a solid session of makin' dem boolits. You could EASILY break this tool by trying to overtighten your shell plate. It is MUCH stronger during the removal process, due to leverage/distance from the front frame member of the press. I demolished a couple of the prototypes during testing, and though they were weak/fast prints, that big hex wrench can lay down some serious torque. Go easy on the tightening.

The photos show one of the final prototypes, printed at very fast/low quality. See "Print Settings" for more information.

Also note, this was designed and tested against a #16 (.223/5.56) shellplate. From feedback it sounds like it might not work too well with every shellplate out there. I'd be willing to do some mods for the 9mm, 40SW, 45ACP, .308 shell plates if anyone discovers a problem but really needs it to work with one of those. Those are the only shell plates I have for my own progressive.

BTW, is it one word, "shellplate" or two, "shell plate"?

Printer Brand:

MakerGear

Printer:

MakerGear M2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Infill:

80%

Notes:

For the real thing, I highly recommend 5 or 6 layers on the bottom (which is actually the top of the tool), 6 layers on the top (which is actually the bottom) and 6 outline layers. Then at least 70% infill, maybe more, possibly print a solid layer every 5 or so infill layers for extra strength.

PLA+ is tougher than ordinary PLA and this tool will benefit. You might also disable your bed fan (there's no bridging, no supports), and really, you want the absolute maximum layer-to-layer adhesion you can manage, so you might even ratchet up the extruder temperature a couple degrees from your usual (there's no where for the thing to generate "strings" either.

ABS might be a pain due to shrinkage - the tolerances are VERY tight in order to maximize strength. I pretty much never use ABS, but if you make it work, that might be nice and tough. Same for PETG, though I guess it shrinks a bit less.

On my MakerGear M2, this takes a bit over an hour to print at the quality/strength settings mentioned above.

title: HHMI's BioInteractive.org 2013 Holiday Lectures on Science Models

description.text:
Howard Hughes Medical Institute's BioInteractive.org teamed up with Makerbot to create 3D models of the kinase BCR-ABL and the ligands ATP, Gleevec, and Dasatinib to illustrate key concepts presented in the 2013 Holiday Lectures on Science, Medicine in the Genomic Era. The Holiday Lectures on Science series brings current research into the science classroom, helping to bridge the gap between textbook curriculum and exciting new research developments. Follow the links below to view animations of these molecular structures in action. ![Alt text](http://www.hhmi.org/sites/default/files/styles/biointeractive_summary/public/Biointeractive/Images/Gleevec-Inhibits-Cancer-Causing-Kinase-BCR-ABL.jpg?itok=GdYE7o1Z )
Gleevec Inhibits Cancer-Causing Kinase BCR-ABL: How the drug Gleevec inactivates BCR-ABL, a mutant kinase that causes chronic myeloid leukemia.
Gleevec-Resistant Form of Kinase BCR-ABL: Other mutations in the BCR-ABL gene can cause resistance to Gleevec, but another drug, Dasatinib, can be used to inactivate BCR-ABL. The models were created with molecular data form the Protein Data Bank (pdb.org) and were optimized with Maxon's Cinema 4D. Print your own models and use them in conjunction with the animations for a truly interactive experience in your classroom! You can learn more and view the full lecture series by navigating to the Holiday Lectures page.

The models were created with molecular data form the Protein Data Bank (pdb.org) and were optimized with Maxon's Cinema 4D. Print your own models and use them in conjunction with the animations and PDF for a truly interactive experience in your classroom!  
Printed with support at standard resolution and 10% infill on a MakerBot Replicator 2.  For best demonstration of the ligand fit, add magnets to the cross-sectioned proteins by super gluing them into the notches.  If printing the full protein models, it is advised to scale down the ligands to about 80%.

title: 50mm Active Cooling Fan Duct v3 for Replicator 1 / Duplicator 4 / FlashForge / CTC

description.text:
EDIT 2017-04-21

Thanks to maker WashingtonApple I have fixed an issue where the opening for the 50mm fan was undersized. I made the vertical distance 51mm to allow for sagging and variations in printed size vs. modeled size.

The new/fixed file is Active_Duct_v3a_fixed. The model was parse through Netfabb, and re-imported into S3D to ensure it renders cleanly.





This has been painfully remixed in Sketchup over way too many hours to make it so that you can run a 50mm fan in a Replicator 1 / Duplicator 4 / FlashForge / CTC printer. I made it specifically for my Flash Forge Creator Pro, but it should work with the rest just as well. It shouldn't go beyond the original dimensions of the v2 Active Duct.

I did this mod because I wanted to be able to quiet my printer down. I've already upgraded most of the fans on both the extruders and the PSU to Gelid Silent fans. I've already modded my FFCP to have a 24vdc -> Adjustable vdc transformer, and I'll be running a Gelid Silent 5 50mm 12v fan at about 6 volts.

The Gelid Silent 5 (50mm) is rated 12.9CFM @ 12v @ 0.15Amp @ 23 dBA @ 4000rpm.
The Paps 414F fans (40mm) are rated 4.7CFM @ 24v @ 22.1 dBA @ 5400rpm

Long of it short, a 50mm fan underdriven will be quieter yet flow more air (assuming we get a linear drop in output).

Thruit00 uses Paps 414F fans, but these are 40mm fans which can be had from Mouser Electronics here: http://www.mouser.com/ProductDetail/ebm-papst/414F/?qs=fklqa858EevxfN57mkkqlw%3D%3D

description.text:
It's pretty much what the name suggests - it's a fan cover for a 40mm fan, with the Star Wars Imperial Navy logo on it. I stretched the outer parts of the logo to make the space needed for proper air flow.

Update 4 May 2017
There was a problem in both versions where one of the "arms" was clipped to half width. That has been fixed and new versions have been uploaded.

Update 2 May 2017
I've extended the space between the logo and the front of the fan to ensure the cover doesn't end up touching the middle of the spinning fan.

I've also added a new, round version of the fan cover. (This one also has the space between the logo and the front of the fan.) Have a look at this new one - I really like it!

See below for information about the two color version (white and black) shown in the cover photo.

HICTOP 3DP-17

Rafts:

No

No

100% for round version

Notes:

The round version of this fan cover should be printed at 100% fill so that the clips are strong enough. Even so, be careful removing the round version from the print bed, and don't try to pull it by the clips. :-)

M600 Change Filament Command

The two color version was made using a single filament printer by inserting the M600 change filament command into the gcode at the point between the end of the circle and the start of the clips. Note that not all printer firmware will support the M600 command and, in the case of the Marlin firmware, it has to be turned on and compiled into the firmware. However, if the command works for you, inserting it a layer before the 4mm point will give you a solid layer of the new filament before the clips start to print.

Alternative Methods

There are many ways to do this two color effect with single filament printers, and here are just two more of them:

  1. One method is to pause the print job at a certain layer height. This link explains how to do that. While these instructions are intended for Simplify3D, it isn't difficult to make the same changes "by hand" in an editor using the gcode from any other slicer.

  2. If you use Simplify3D, another method is to splitting the print job into two halves. This link explains how to do that.

I'd be happy to add specific instructions for other slicers if people wish to send them to me!

This actual remix does NOT require any printed parts. You simply need the led light strips and clear packing tape. I wanted quick and easy lighting for the Hypercube I am building and came up with this simple solution. KISS always works best (keep it simple stupid)

Search Ebay or Aliexpress, for COB Auto Light Strip. You can get them for about $1 delivered.

These strips are 12V and run easily off the power supplies. My picture shows how it is mounted using masking tape, so you can see how to put the tape. You simply take a small piece about 1.5 inches, tape the front of the light and then set the light in the 2020 track and pull the tape back over the top and tape it to the top. It forms a triangle and it is very stable. I use the slightly thicker clear packing tape, but any will do.

The picture of 2 yellow lights shows how it looks from the bottom or inside the cube and the white shows how it would look from the top looking down inside the cube. I still can't get over how quick and easy this was, SIMPLE.

title: Endoscope Holder for Rostock Max V2

description.text:
This is a small endoscope/borescope holder for the Rostock Max V2 printer which has been upgraded with the 713Maker aluminum effector plate for ball cup joints. It may work with other effector plates.

The tab slot will slip right onto one of the three tabs (which are usually used to hold layer cooling fans.)

The vertical distance from the bottom of the tab slot (same as the bottom of the effector plate) to the lowest point of the tube is 13.25mm. This means the tip of the nozzle must extend a bit more than 13.25mm below the bottom surface of the effector plate so that the holder will clear the print. The tube is angled 10 degrees down from horizontal toward the nozzle.

I did not provide a hole to fasten the holder to the effector plate tab - you can drill one that suits your positioning.

A couple important dimensions:
Tube diameter: 7.75mm as printed. Too small? It can be drilled out a bit, the walls are 1.4mm thick. Too big? You can cut a slot the length of the tube and squeeze the tube with a twist-tie or similar.

Slot dimensions: 8.25mm x 2.0mm x 15.5mm as printed

Print settings:

Layer height: 0.15mm
Printing speed: 30mm/s
Infill: 100% although less will work too
No support needed

description.text:
I grew up in the 80s during the golden age of arcade machines, so I have always wished I had an arcade machine with real arcade joystick + buttons. Now that I have a 3D printer, I thought I should put it to good use and make myself a desktop arcade machine. I used TinkerCAD to do all the 3D modelling. Also, I wanted my arcade machine to have a lot of detail, so I also created things like vintage design coin slot and also created artwork which I sent to a commercial printer to have them printed on vinyl sticker.

This is not the first 3D printed arcade machine, there are already many around. However, there were certain things which I prefer it to be designed differently. Take for example the palm rest area. I did some testing and found that without sufficient space to rest your palm, you will get tired very quickly. Most of the existing designs I found had this issue, so I made sure my design had a big palm rest.

I should note that I actually designed and printed these parts before receiving the actual parts like the LCD screen, controller, speaker, amplifier etc. 3D printing takes quite a lot of time and I didn't want to wait till everything I ordered has arrived in the mail before I started printing. So, some of the parts were designed with some flexibility in terms of how it would be laid out. Also, this was a learning process for me as I am still relatively new to 3D printing, so some parts have gone through many changes as I experimented with the design. I believe all the files I uploaded should be correct, but in case there are any mistakes, do let me know.

Please understand that I am sharing these files AS IS. You do need to have a decent knowledge of 3D printing, Raspberry Pi, soldering, etc. in order to put it all together.

More detail over here: https://hackaday.io/project/20093-desktop-arcade-machine-3d-printed-retropie

Printer:

Zonestar P802QA (based on Prusa i3)

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Notes:

I used PLA for stiffness. All my 3D models were designed to be printed without the need for any support structures. You will need a 3D printer with a minimum print volume of 220mm x 220mm x 120mm in order to print these files.

Parts were printed at 0.2mm to 0.3mm layer height with 0.4mm nozzle. Most were printed with 100% infill, except for the large body pieces which were printed at 30% infill.

Finishing Touches

Most of the main pieces are held together using nuts and bolts, or screws. You will need M3 bolts of various lengths (probably 10mm - 16mm) and some screws. I am afraid I lost the specs of the screw I used, but it's about 10mm long and 2.5mm diameter. These were use for the marquee pieces.

I sprayed primer putty and sanded it down to a smooth finish before spraying matte black paint for the final finish. You want to make sure you sand the top edges of "Body - Front Left" and "Body - Front Right" so that they are nice and smooth, cause otherwise, when you rest your hands on them, the sharp edges will get irritating quite quickly.

In order to make it look like a commercial quality product, I did a lot of research into the designs of the artwork for old arcade machines. I took inspiration from them to create my own artwork for my arcade machine and had it commercially printed on vinyl stickers.

For the marquee, cut the clear PVC sheet to 210mm x 45mm. You can apply the sticker on top before inserting it.

Connecting Everything Together
  • The controller's USB connector will plug into the Raspberry Pi's USB socket.
  • The power connecter for the display will plug into the Raspberry Pi's USB socket.
  • The HDMI out on the Raspberry Pi needs to be connected to the HDMI input on the display controller board.
  • The speaker needs to be soldered to the amplifier circuit, and the amplfier circuit's power input needs to the connected to the Raspberry Pi's GPIO pin 4 & 6 for the 5V power supply. You also need to solder an earphone jack connector to the amplifier circuit and plug that into the Raspberry Pi's audio socket.
  • Solder together the LEDs and wire it to a USB connector. Plug it into the Raspberry Pi's USB socket.

So, everything is powered directly from the Raspberry Pi. The only cable going into the arcade machine is the Raspberry Pi's power supply cable.

Software Setup

You will need to get RetroPie setup and configured. For that, please check out RetroPie's website (https://retropie.org.uk) and Google for anything you need. All the resources you need are out there!

QUESTION: Done everything and turned it on, but nothing appears on the display, what's wrong?

The first time you try to power up the full setup, make sure to power the display from a SEPARATE USB power supply FIRST, before turning on your Raspberry Pi. The display needs to be active first, otherwise your RPi would not use HDMI output for display. Also, do connect a keyboard to your RPi.

After powering up your Raspberry Pi, let it boot up all the way until Emulation Station/Attract Mode comes up (depending on your setup), then exit to terminal.

Open the Raspberry Pi configuration file for editing with this command:

sudo nano /boot/config.txt

Use arrows to get to the end of the file and add these 3 lines:

#Always force HDMI output and enable HDMI sound

hdmi_force_hotplug=1
hdmi_drive=2

Save the changes by pressing CTRL + O and ENTER

Exit the editor by pressing CTRL + X

Now you can turn everything off, reconnect your display's power supply to RPi's USB socket. Now when you turn it on, your RPi will default to HDMI output even though the screen is powering up later than your RPi.

QUESTION: Isn't it easier to just use a laser cutter to cut MDF for all the large pieces?

Indeed, that would have been simpler and faster, and I actually considered that option first, but unfortunately, I don't have access to a laser cutter. Sending it to a commercial facility to do that would have cost me a lot more than 3D printing it myself, so here we are!

Anyway, doing this entire project with 3D printing was actually a good thing for me, because it allowed me to practice my 3D modelling skills and I learnt many things about creating designs specifically for 3D printing.

Overall, I came out of this project having vastly improved my 3D printing skills and gained a lot more experience which I am sure will be helpful in my future projects! =)

title: ROADS - Old and New - Part A

description.text:
'ROADS!' (which is what I thought Ray Winstone et al were bellowing in the movie 'King Arthur' until I listened a bit closer). Anyway...roads - lots of 'em. Principally designed for the 28mm wargames market but suitable for D&D, historical dioramas etc etc, the modular-build roads represent a variety of styles, largely of a roman vintage, shown initially as a brand new road, and then the same one in a post-roman / Dark Ages state after decay, lack of maintenance and people 'borrowing' stone to build dwellings or a new shrubbery (for all you Monty P. fans out there!) have taken their toll on the surface. All new roads have a slight camber, a gutter and a drain at the junctions.

Part A (here) represents close-paved roads probably used more for towns and cities in the posh areas.
Part B - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2233811 represents a more stone-mosaic style road suitable for regular roman roads
Part C http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2282662 is a small-shingle/cobbled style of road - unfortunately there will be a bit of a delay on the 'old' one as I accidentally overwrote an unmerged model with a merged model, and now I can't use that as a template for the other shapes - I'll carry on when I've finished banging my head against the wall !!
Part D http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2246249 is a packed earth road for those out-of-the-way roads that didn't get much traffic or attention. The old version is basically a mud trail. It dawned on me later that the new variety could be almost any period road.
Each set of roads contains :-

  • a straight piece (the 'old set' in Part A has two for variety)
  • a short straight piece (half of above)
  • a double straight (almost a double straight as it was coming off the end of my printer)
  • a 45% bend
  • a T-junction
  • a crossroad

The plastic wargames figures shown are Gripping Beast 28mm plastic vikings, plus one or two other figures from my models I've also put on Thingiverse. I'm painting the saxons, honest, but slowly...

Printer:

Flashforge Creator Pro

Resolution:

Fine

Notes:

I kept the rafts for these roads as they seemed to gave a better grip on material surfaces. The long straight may need a raft as the corners have a desire to lift off the printer bed without one.

If you're picking the roads by file name, they are all in the sequence
[Part letter] [Old or new] [road type] _ number
where Road types are:
str - straight
hstr - half straight
lstr - long straight
45b - 45 % bend
tjx - T junction
xrd - crossroad

So:
a_o_lstr_1 will be the first long straight for Roads Part A in the Old style (beat up)
Hope that makes sense!

Painting

I used a gesso undercoat, but an acrylic spray may be needed to ensure that the depths/cracks of the paving get covered completely (otherwise the acrylic wash runs off )
I used a black acrylic wash to make sure the cracks/gaps are covered, then dry-brush the surface with whatever colour you desire. (I inked the cracks here to get them to show up in the photos)
I used a soluble acylic matt varnish to top them off

description.text:
If you print it out please remember to share your make. It's always good to how other people have used the models :) Thanks!

This was designed for use on an IKEA Lack table allowing you to cut a various sizes of holes in the table and inset the grommet. Just choose your size for what you need and get printing! I used the grommet in my 3D printer enclosure but could be used anywhere. Check that out here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2212749

A square version can be found here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2265185

Updated (12/04/2017) - I have added all metric sizes in relation to the hole cutter linked below. All grommets are set to be 53mm deep.

Metric - 25, 32 ,38 ,45 ,50 ,56 ,62mm

Updated (22/04/2017) - I have added all imperial sizes in relation to the hole cutter linked below. All grommets are set to be 53mm deep

Imperial - 3/4", 7/8", 1 1/8", 1 1/4", 1 1/2", 1 3/4", 2", 2 1/2", 3", 3 1/2", 4", 5”

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

Prusa Mk2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.20

Infill:

20%

Notes:

When you print this be sure to split the cover from the body of the grommet. This can be done in all the slicer programs. this will give you the two parts.

E.g.

  • Simplify3D Its under "Mesh->Separate Connected Surfaces" in S3D.
  • Slic3r - Use the split button on the toolbar.

Mark and drill a pilot hole straight through the whole table. This will act as your guide when doing the next cut. Then cut a 50mm hole in the top side of the table. Drill through from the other side using the pilot hole as your guide. Insert the grommet. It will be a tight fit in the last 2-3mm as it is designed as a push fit to clamp onto the hole you have just created. Pass through the cable and put on the cover. Job done!

These are probably the best value hole cutters you can get for various sizes and will be more than enough for an LACK table.

UK - Metric https://www.amazon.co.uk/Wolfcraft-Holesaw-Blades-Pilot-Drill/dp/B0001P1968/ref=sr_1_2?s=diy&ie;=UTF8&qid;=1491861349&sr;=1-2&keywords;=50mm+hole+cutter US - Imperial https://www.amazon.com/Hole-pieces-Mandrels-Install-Plate/dp/B001OC1958/ref=sr_1_3?ie=UTF8&qid;=1492890689&sr;=8-3&keywords;=hole+cutter
